A 4-year-old girl has experienced two prior episodes of mild acute pancreatitis over 18 months, both resolving with supportive care. Workup showed no gallstones, normal triglyceride levels, no anatomic anomalies on MRCP, no toxin or drug exposure, and normal metabolic screening. Genetic testing reveals a SPINK1 mutation. She now presents with a third episode, severe with evidence of pancreatic necrosis on imaging. After recovery, what is the most likely long-term outcome?\
\
A. Complete resolution without long-term consequences  \
B. Intermittent pancreatitis until surgical correction  \
C. Progression to chronic pancreatitis  \
D. Development of exocrine or endocrine insufficiency  \
E. Recurrent acute episodes without progression  \
\
